The issue appears to be this check:

`pubspec.getTimeStamp() > packages.getTimeStamp()`

which takes a long time to catch up with the time stamps on the local file system.

Oddly, I *thought* I was addressing this exact issue with this code:

      sdk.run(COMMAND, pair.first, workingDir, new ProcessAdapter() {
        @Override
        public void processTerminated(ProcessEvent event) {
          // Refresh to ensure Dart Plugin sees .packages and doesn't mistakenly nag to run pub.
          LocalFileSystem.getInstance().refreshAndFindFileByPath(workingDir.getPath() + "/" + FlutterConstants.PACKAGES_FILE);
        }
      });

(in `io.flutter.actions.FlutterPackagesGetAction#perform`).

@alexander-doroshko : any thoughts?  Is there a better way to refresh the `.packages` file?  I don't think doing it in the inspection is correct (since it's a read action).

